===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|knowleche||knowledge}}, of uncertain formation. The first element is ultimately identical with {{term|know}}, but the second is obscure (neither Old Norse {{term|-leikr|lang=non}} nor Old English {{m|ang|-lāċ}} would have given ''-leche'' as found in the earliest Middle English citations). Compare {{etyl|enm|-}} {{m|enm|knowlechen||to acknowledge}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{m|ang|cnāwelǣċing}}, {{m|ang|cnāwlǣċ||acknowledgment}}, and {{term|know}}. Compare also {{term|freeledge|lang=en}}.
* <span style="font-size:85%;">The noun originally provided a counterpart to the now-obsolete verb ''to knowledge'' (see below), but was very early adapted to be the noun equivalent of {{term|know}}.</span>

